<p class="css-cizdwu eb5pyrn1">The Metropolitan Museum, Whitney Museum, Guggenheim, Museum of Modern Art, Metropolitan Opera, Carnegie Hall and New York Philharmonic announced temporary closures.</p>
<p class="css-11eh2b0 e4e4i5l2"><span class="css-me3p27"><div data-testid="todays-date" aria-label="March 12, 2020">March 12, 2020</div></span><span class="css-1dydysp e4e4i5l3"></span><span class="css-9voj2j">By<!-- --> <span class="css-1baulvz" itemprop="name">Robin Pogrebin</span> and <span class="css-1baulvz last-byline" itemprop="name">Michael Cooper</span></span></p>
<p class="css-cizdwu eb5pyrn1">Facing restrictions on audience size and concern from actors and audiences about health risks during the coronavirus pandemic, the industry announced that shows will be shuttered through April 12.</p>
<p class="css-11eh2b0 e4e4i5l2"><span class="css-me3p27"><div data-testid="todays-date" aria-label="May 12, 2020">May 12, 2020</div></span><span class="css-1dydysp e4e4i5l3"></span><span class="css-9voj2j">By<!-- --> <span class="css-1baulvz last-byline" itemprop="name">Michael Paulson</span></span></p>
<p class="css-cizdwu eb5pyrn1">First South by Southwest was canceled and Coachella got postponed. Now the live-music business is facing billions of dollars in lost income as its two largest promoters shut down shows.</p>
